            The second morning starts with questions.

            I ask as they walk, "So how do the water plants communicate?"

            The ground squelches underfoot, wetter than yesterday, and my boots leave deep impressions that immediately fill with dark water.

            Brightbloom bounces enthusiastically and says,
            "*Oh, it's wonderful!* Completely different from Territory One! Forest plants use fungal networks mostly—underground connections, very elegant—but here everything's about water!"

            Streamwalker adds, "Chemical signals through water currents—like scent on wind, but liquid. The water carries meaning."

            I ask, "So they… smell to each other? Through water?"

            Brightbloom's flowers brighten as they answer,
            "Taste, maybe? _Hard to translate!_ But yes—plants release specific compounds, water carries them to neighbors, neighbors interpret the chemical composition. *Very efficient network!*"

            Scout bounces through a shallow pool, sending up spray—apparently testing the water-communication system through enthusiastic splashing.

            I gesture to Brightbloom and ask, "And you? How do your flowers communicate? I've noticed they bloom and close based on mood."

            Brightbloom's entire structure glows with pleasure as they say,
            "Oh, you've been watching! Yes—flowers are multilayered communication. Color signals mood to anyone watching, scent carries chemical information, petal patterns encode specific messages—watch this!"

            Brightbloom stops bouncing. Their flowers—maybe forty bright orange blooms scattered across the bush structure—begin opening and closing in deliberate patterns, three on the left opening, then five on the right, then two at the top—like musical notes played on a floral instrument.

            Brightbloom explains, "That pattern means 'safe path ahead'—and this one"—different flowers bloom, creating a wave across the canopy—"means 'water nearby, approach with awareness.' Very useful for territory coordination!"

            I say, "That's beautiful—like sign language but with flowers."

            Brightbloom continues, "Exactly! Though most plants can't see it—I'm signaling to mobile guides mostly, ones who can observe visual patterns. For rooted plants I use scent-based communication. Flexibility is key!"

            Streamwalker makes a gentle sighing sound and adds, "Brightbloom speaks seven plant dialects. Very accomplished communicator."

            Brightbloom says to Streamwalker, "Oh, Streamwalker, you speak just as many! Your music is gorgeous, all those tones and harmonics—"

            Streamwalker replies, "But not as enthusiastically," with what might have been affection.

            I smile. The guide dynamic is growing familiar—Brightbloom's bouncing energy and Streamwalker's flowing calm. Different from Leafwhisper and Rootwalker, but comfortable in its own way.

            The wetlands deepen as we walk. More standing water appears, less solid ground. The path becomes a careful route between pools, stepping on reed clusters and raised patches that Streamwalker tests before crossing.
          </text>
