          <text>
            Streamwalker says, "Watch your footing here. The ground deceives. Not all solid patches hold weight."

            Brightbloom says, *"Test before trusting — very important in wetlands! The soil loves to surprise you!"*

            I step carefully, following Streamwalker's exact path; my boots find mostly solid ground — spongy and wet but supporting my weight. Then my left foot goes through — a complete collapse. My boot punches through what looks like solid moss and keeps going, down through water and mud and nothing; my leg is sinking fast.

            ¶

            I yelp and throw my weight sideways—

            Streamwalker, already moving, says, "Stay still. Don't pull."

            I freeze. My left leg is buried to mid-thigh; my right foot barely supports my weight on questionable ground. Panic flutters in my chest.

            Brightbloom says, *"You're okay! This happens — totally normal! We've got you!"*

            Streamwalker's vines extend smoothly, wrapping around my outstretched arm — secure, not tight. Streamwalker says, "Lean toward me. Let the vines take weight."

            I lean. The vines hold — strong, steady, completely confident.

            Streamwalker says, "On three we lift — one. Two. Three."

            The vines pull: steady, patient, impossibly strong. My leg comes free with a wet sucking sound, mud and water cascading off my boot.

            Streamwalker guides me to a solid patch, testing and confirming the ground.

            Streamwalker says, "There. Safe now. The ground gave way, as it does. But you're fine."

            My heart is pounding.

            I say, "That was—"

            Brightbloom says, *"Exciting! Your first wetland collapse! We should celebrate — well, not the scary part, but celebrate handling it well! You stayed still, listened to instructions — very excellent crisis response!"*

            Buddy observes, "The mud took your boot halfway. I'm detecting elevated heart rate. Would you like breathing exercises —"

            "I'm fine, Buddy," I say. I look down at my mud-caked leg: my entire left side is soaked, boot full of swamp water, pants plastered with dark muck. "I'm... actually fine."

            And I am — surprised, still buzzing with adrenaline, but not panicking, not spiraling into fear about what could have happened. The guides handled it — just handled it. Routine, apparently — based on Brightbloom's enthusiasm about a "first wetland collapse," it probably is.

            I ask, "Does that happen often?"

            Streamwalker says, "Every third or fourth traveler. The wetlands test footing. We test travelers. You did well — stayed calm, followed direction."

            Brightbloom says, *"Plus you're fine! Totally fine! No injuries! Much better than the traveler who panicked and thrashed and ended up chest-deep — that took twenty minutes to extract! You were very efficient!"*

            Scout rolls cautiously to me, bumping my ankle gently — checking in.

            I say, "I'm good, Scout. Just muddy."
          </text>
