          <text>
            Scout bounces once—reassured—then immediately returns to investigating a nearby flower cluster, apparently satisfied that I will survive minor swamp incidents as we continue. My left boot squelches with every step, mud gradually working its way between my toes—uncomfortable but manageable—and my heart rate settles back to a normal walking rhythm.

            And somewhere in that settling, I realize something.

            ¶

            I'd trusted the guides. Not hoped they'd help, not desperately wished for rescue—actually trusted. When my leg went through and Streamwalker said, "Stay still," I'd stayed still. When they said, "Lean toward me," I'd leaned. No hesitation—just trust.

            Now I'd just been pulled out of a swamp hole and my primary thought is «well that was routine.»

            Streamwalker observed, "You're smiling."

            I say, "I am?"

            Brightbloom confirmed, "*Very pleased expression!* — *Happy about the mud?* — *Some plants love mud!* — *Are humans similar?*"

            I say, "Not about the mud." I wipe wet leaves off my jacket. "About… I don't know—realizing I've gotten better at this? At traveling? At trusting the process?"

            Streamwalker said simply, "You have—first day you were uncertain at the river crossing; today you stepped into questionable ground because you were following the path, not frozen by fear of mistakes—growth."

            Brightbloom added, "*Very significant growth!* — *Territory One guides sent excellent documentation about you — they said you adapted quickly, learned fast, asked good questions. We're seeing all of that! You're becoming a proper traveler!*"

            I say, "A proper traveler who sinks into swamps." I'm still smiling.

            Streamwalker makes their gentle laugh-sound and says, "Both can be true. Water teaches flexibility."

            We walk through afternoon wetlands. The sun is stronger here without the forest canopy, warming my mud-soaked clothes into merely damp unpleasantness. Scout investigates every pool and reed cluster. Brightbloom points out interesting flowers and occasionally demonstrates communication patterns—blooming sequences that mean "rest stop ahead," "water level rising," or "excellent weather, isn't it lovely?"

            Streamwalker leads with patient grace, testing ground and adjusting our path when needed.

            And I follow—still careful, still learning, still occasionally thinking wistfully about Leafwhisper's information cascades or Rootwalker's grounded solidity. But I'm also present—trusting these guides, this team, this journey.

            By evening, we reach another raised platform shelter, this one surrounded by tall purple reeds that sway in a gentle breeze.
          </text>
